---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import SiteNav from "../../components/SiteNav.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="Examples | Linkar" description="Choose the right bundled Linkar example pack based on what you want to learn: basic template authoring, chaining, binding overrides, pack selection, or remote packs.">
  <div class="page-shell">
    <SiteNav />
    <main class="section-page">
      <section class="page-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Examples</p>
        <h1 class="page-title">Bundled packs you can read and run.</h1>
        <p class="lede page-lede">
          Use this page to pick the smallest example that answers your question. The bundled packs
          are not filler data. Each one exists to clarify one part of the runtime model.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section page-section-tight">
        <div class="split-grid">
          <article class="content-card">
            <h3>Fastest way to explore</h3>
            <pre><code>linkar test simple_echo --pack ./examples/packs/basic
linkar test fastq_stats --pack ./examples/packs/basic
linkar test produce_message --pack ./examples/packs/chaining</code></pre>
          </article>

          <article class="content-card">
            <h3>How to choose</h3>
            <p>
              Start with `basic` if you are learning template shape. Move to `chaining` when you
              want one template to feed another. Use `binding_overrides` when you want to compare
              pack defaults with explicit caller control.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section page-section-tight">
        <div class="card-grid two-up">
          <article class="feature-card">
            <h3>Basic</h3>
            <p>
              Start here for the current template contract. This pack shows `run.command`,
              `run.sh`, `run.py`, declared outputs, file inputs, boolean flags, and local tests.
            </p>
            <pre><code>examples/packs/basic
  simple_echo
  simple_file_input
  simple_boolean_flag
  download_test_data
  fastq_stats
  pixi_echo
  pixi_pytest</code></pre>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <h3>Chaining</h3>
            <p>
              Open this when you want to see pack-level default binding in action. The key lesson is
              that template-to-template connection lives in the pack, not in manual operator steps.
            </p>
            <pre><code>examples/packs/chaining
  linkar_pack.yaml
  templates/
    produce_message
    consume_message</code></pre>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <h3>Binding overrides</h3>
            <p>
              Use this when you want to compare three things directly: project history, a pack's
              default binding, and an explicit override binding passed by the caller.
            </p>
            <pre><code>examples/packs/binding_overrides
  linkar_pack.yaml
  override_binding/
  templates/
    produce_data
    consume_data</code></pre>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <h3>Pack management and remote</h3>
            <p>
              Use `pack_management` for duplicate template ids and active-pack selection. Use
              `remote` once local packs are clear and you want to see `git+` references and
              revision-aware provenance.
            </p>
            <pre><code>examples/packs/pack_management
examples/packs/remote</code></pre>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
